No, this is extremely dangerous! Binding all POST data directly to your model creates a **mass assignment vulnerability**. Attackers can inject hidden fields to modify properties they shouldn't access, like admin flags or role IDs.

**VULNERABLE CODE**:

```php
<?php
require_once 'config.php';

class User {
    public $id;
    public $username;
    public $email;
    public $is_admin;      // Sensitive!
    public $role_id;       // Sensitive!
    public $account_balance; // Sensitive!

    private $pdo;

    public function __construct($pdo) {
        $this->pdo = $pdo;
    }

    // VULNERABLE: Mass assignment from user input
    public function updateFromRequest($data) {
        foreach ($data as $key => $value) {
            if (property_exists($this, $key)) {
                $this->$key = $value;  // Blindly assigns ALL properties!
            }
        }
    }

    public function save() {
        $sql = "UPDATE users SET username = ?, email = ?, is_admin = ?, role_id = ?, account_balance = ? WHERE id = ?";
        $stmt = $this->pdo->prepare($sql);
        $stmt->execute([$this->username, $this->email, $this->is_admin, $this->role_id, $this->account_balance, $this->id]);
    }
}

// Controller handling profile update
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $user = new User($pdo);
    $user->id = $_SESSION['user_id'];
    $user->updateFromRequest($_POST);  // DANGEROUS!
    $user->save();
    echo "Profile updated!";
}
```

**Attack Payload**:
```html
<!-- Normal form -->
<form method="POST" action="/profile/update">
    <input name="username" value="attacker">
    <input name="email" value="attacker@evil.com">
    <!-- Attacker adds hidden fields via browser dev tools or curl -->
    <input type="hidden" name="is_admin" value="1">
    <input type="hidden" name="role_id" value="1">
    <input type="hidden" name="account_balance" value="999999">
    <button type="submit">Update Profile</button>
</form>
```

```bash
# Or via curl:
curl -X POST https://target.com/profile/update \
  -d "username=attacker&email=hacker@evil.com&is_admin=1&role_id=1&account_balance=999999" \
  -H "Cookie: session=victim_session_id"
```

**Why This Is Dangerous**:
- Attacker can elevate their own privileges to admin by setting `is_admin=1`
- Attacker can modify account balances for financial fraud
- Attacker can change role assignments bypassing access controls
- Any database column mapped to a property becomes exploitable

**SECURE VERSION**:

```php
<?php
require_once 'config.php';

class User {
    public $id;
    public $username;
    public $email;
    public $is_admin;
    public $role_id;
    public $account_balance;

    private $pdo;

    // SECURITY: Whitelist of fields users can modify
    private static $fillable = ['username', 'email'];

    // SECURITY: Fields that should NEVER be mass-assigned
    private static $guarded = ['id', 'is_admin', 'role_id', 'account_balance'];

    public function __construct($pdo) {
        $this->pdo = $pdo;
    }

    // SECURE: Only allow whitelisted fields
    public function updateFromRequest(array $data): void {
        $sanitizedData = $this->filterFillable($data);

        foreach ($sanitizedData as $key => $value) {
            $this->$key = $this->sanitizeValue($key, $value);
        }
    }

    private function filterFillable(array $data): array {
        return array_intersect_key(
            $data,
            array_flip(self::$fillable)
        );
    }

    private function sanitizeValue(string $key, $value) {
        switch ($key) {
            case 'username':
                return preg_replace('/[^a-zA-Z0-9_]/', '', $value);
            case 'email':
                return filter_var($value, FILTER_SANITIZE_EMAIL);
            default:
                return htmlspecialchars($value, ENT_QUOTES, 'UTF-8');
        }
    }

    public function save(): bool {
        // Only save whitelisted fields
        $sql = "UPDATE users SET username = ?, email = ? WHERE id = ?";
        $stmt = $this->pdo->prepare($sql);
        return $stmt->execute([$this->username, $this->email, $this->id]);
    }
}

// Secure controller
if ($_SERVER['REQUEST_METHOD'] === 'POST') {
    $user = new User($pdo);
    $user->id = $_SESSION['user_id'];
    $user->updateFromRequest($_POST);  // Now safe - only fillable fields
    $user->save();
    echo "Profile updated!";
}
```

**Key Security Controls**:
- **Whitelist approach**: Only explicitly allowed fields (`$fillable`) can be updated
- **Guarded fields**: Sensitive properties are protected from mass assignment
- **Input sanitization**: Each field type gets appropriate sanitization
- **Minimal UPDATE**: SQL only touches allowed columns

